Launch EC2 via NICE DCV
Prerequisites
Basic Linux command line knowledge
Understanding of SSH connections
Familiarity with text editors (nano or vi)
AWS account with EC2 access permissions
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Launch an EC2 instance on AWS
Install and configure NICE DCV server on Linux
Configure security groups for DCV access
Connect to the instance using NICE DCV client
Verify remote desktop functionality
Environment Setup
Note: This lab uses AWS EC2. You'll need:

An active AWS account
Access to AWS Management Console
NICE DCV client installed on your local machine (download from https://download.nice-dcv.com/)
Task 1: Launch EC2 Instance
Step 1: Create EC2 Instance
Log into AWS Management Console
Navigate to EC2 Dashboard
Click Launch Instance
Configure the following:
Name: dcv-lab-instance
AMI: Ubuntu Server 22.04 LTS (64-bit x86)
Instance Type: t2.medium (minimum for graphical desktop)
Key Pair: Create new or select existing key pair (save the .pem file securely)
Step 2: Configure Storage
Set root volume to 30 GB gp3
Keep default settings for other options
Step 3: Review and Launch
Click Launch Instance
Wait for instance state to show Running (2-3 minutes)
Note the Public IPv4 address from instance details
Task 2: Configure Security Groups
Step 1: Modify Security Group Rules
Select your instance in EC2 console
Click on the Security tab
Click on the security group link
Click Edit inbound rules
Add the following rules:
Type: SSH
Protocol: TCP
Port: 22
Source: My IP (or 0.0.0.0/0 for testing only)

Type: Custom TCP
Protocol: TCP
Port: 8443
Source: My IP (or 0.0.0.0/0 for testing only)

Type: Custom UDP
Protocol: UDP
Port: 8443
Source: My IP (or 0.0.0.0/0 for testing only)
Click Save rules
Note: Port 8443 is the default NICE DCV port. Using "My IP" is more secure than 0.0.0.0/0.

Task 3: Install NICE DCV Server
Step 1: Connect to Instance via SSH
# Change permissions on your key file
chmod 400 your-key-pair.pem

# Connect to instance (replace with your IP and key file)
ssh -i your-key-pair.pem ubuntu@YOUR_INSTANCE_PUBLIC_IP
Step 2: Update System and Install Desktop Environment
# Update package lists
sudo apt update

# Install Ubuntu desktop environment (this takes 5-10 minutes)
sudo apt install -y ubuntu-desktop

# Install required dependencies
sudo apt install -y mesa-utils
Step 3: Download and Install NICE DCV Server
# Download NICE DCV server package
wget https://d1uj6qtbmh3dt5.cloudfront.net/2023.0/Servers/nice-dcv-2023.0-15065-ubuntu2204-x86_64.tgz

# Extract the archive
tar -xvzf nice-dcv-2023.0-15065-ubuntu2204-x86_64.tgz

# Navigate to extracted directory
cd nice-dcv-2023.0-15065-ubuntu2204-x86_64

# Install DCV server
sudo apt install -y ./nice-dcv-server_2023.0.15065-1_amd64.ubuntu2204.deb

# Install DCV web viewer (optional, for browser access)
sudo apt install -y ./nice-dcv-web-viewer_2023.0.15065-1_amd64.ubuntu2204.deb
Step 4: Configure DCV Server
# Create DCV configuration directory if not exists
sudo mkdir -p /etc/dcv

# Set password for ubuntu user
sudo passwd ubuntu
# Enter a strong password when prompted

# Enable and start DCV server
sudo systemctl enable dcvserver
sudo systemctl start dcvserver
Step 5: Create DCV Session
# Create a console session for the ubuntu user
sudo dcv create-session --type=console --owner ubuntu my-session

# Verify session is running
sudo dcv list-sessions
Expected Output:

Session: my-session (owner: ubuntu, type: console)
Task 4: Connect Using DCV Client
Step 1: Install DCV Client (On Your Local Machine)
Windows/Mac: Download from https://download.nice-dcv.com/
Linux:
wget https://d1uj6qtbmh3dt5.cloudfront.net/2023.0/Clients/nice-dcv-viewer_2023.0.5483-1_amd64.ubuntu2204.deb
sudo apt install -y ./nice-dcv-viewer_2023.0.5483-1_amd64.ubuntu2204.deb
Step 2: Connect to DCV Session
Open NICE DCV Viewer application
Enter connection string: YOUR_INSTANCE_PUBLIC_IP:8443
Click Trust & Connect when prompted about certificate
Enter credentials:
Username: ubuntu
Password: (password you set earlier)
Click Login
Step 3: Access Desktop Environment
You should now see the Ubuntu desktop interface
The connection is encrypted and optimized for remote access
Verification
Verify DCV Installation
# Check DCV server status
sudo systemctl status dcvserver

# Verify DCV session
sudo dcv list-sessions

# Check DCV version
dcv version
Verify Remote Access
In the DCV client window, open a terminal (right-click desktop > Open Terminal)
Run the following commands:
# Check display variable
echo $DISPLAY

# Test graphics capability
glxinfo | grep "OpenGL"

# Verify you're connected via DCV
who
Test Desktop Functionality
Open Firefox browser from Applications menu
Open Files application
Create a test text file on the desktop
Verify mouse and keyboard input work smoothly
Troubleshooting Tips
Cannot connect to instance via SSH:

Verify security group allows SSH (port 22) from your IP
Check key pair permissions: chmod 400 your-key.pem
Verify instance is in "running" state
DCV client cannot connect:

Confirm security group allows TCP/UDP 8443
Verify DCV server is running: sudo systemctl status dcvserver
Check session exists: sudo dcv list-sessions
Ensure you're using the correct public IP address
Black screen after connecting:

Desktop environment may still be installing
Wait 2-3 minutes and reconnect
Verify desktop is installed: dpkg -l | grep ubuntu-desktop
Session not found error:

Recreate session: sudo dcv create-session --type=console --owner ubuntu my-session
Ensure you're using the correct session name in connection
Cleanup (Optional)
To avoid AWS charges:

Terminate EC2 instance from AWS Console
Delete associated security groups if no longer needed
Remove key pairs if not reusing
Conclusion
You have successfully:

Launched an EC2 instance on AWS
Installed and configured NICE DCV server on Ubuntu
Set up appropriate security group rules for remote access
Connected to the instance using NICE DCV client
Verified full remote desktop functionality
Significance: NICE DCV provides high-performance remote desktop access to cloud instances, enabling graphics-intensive applications, development environments, and remote workstations. This is particularly valuable for:

Remote work scenarios requiring full desktop environments
Running graphics applications in the cloud
Accessing powerful cloud compute resources with a desktop interface
Secure, encrypted remote access to Linux systems
The skills learned here form the foundation for cloud-based virtual desktop infrastructure (VDI) and remote development environments.
